You’re describing something real, but it’s important to keep it anchored in biology and social cognition — not metaphysics — because that’s where its power actually comes from.

What you’re feeling is high-bandwidth interpersonal coupling, not telekinesis.

Here’s what’s actually happening, cleanly:

1. Eye contact is a privileged neural channel
Direct eye contact activates a dense stack of systems simultaneously:
	•	face recognition (fusiform gyrus)
	•	threat / salience detection (amygdala)
	•	intention modeling (theory-of-mind networks)
	•	autonomic regulation (heart rate, breathing)
	•	mirror neuron systems

Most communication routes through language → cortex → interpretation.
Eye contact routes straight into pre-verbal layers.

That’s why it feels immediate and “unmediated.”

2. Pupils, micro-muscles, and timing carry information
Humans unconsciously read:
	•	pupil dilation
	•	blink rate
	•	saccades (micro eye movements)
	•	facial tension
	•	posture symmetry
	•	breath timing

These are not symbolic. They’re state signals.

Your nervous system evolved to detect them because, historically, missing them meant death or social exile.

So when you “lock eyes,” you’re not sending thoughts — you’re synchronizing states.

3. Synchrony feels like transmission
When two people enter tight mutual attention:
	•	heart rates can align
	•	breathing patterns converge
	•	posture mirrors
	•	prediction errors drop

When prediction error drops fast, the brain experiences it as clarity or knowing.

Subjectively, that feels like:

“I didn’t think this — I received it.”

But nothing paranormal happened.
Two systems simply reached low-latency mutual modeling.

4. Why it feels dialect-dependent
You nailed this part perfectly.

Everyone has different “dialects” because:
	•	culture shapes baseline expressions
	•	trauma rewires threat thresholds
	•	training (military, sports, acting) sharpens signal clarity
	•	trust determines how much data someone allows to leak

That’s why eye contact can feel intimate, confrontational, or meaningless depending on the pairing.

5. Why people reach for mystical language
Because there’s no good everyday vocabulary for:
	•	pre-linguistic communication
	•	autonomic state coupling
	•	embodied inference

So the brain reaches for words like:
	•	soul
	•	energy
	•	telepathy

Not because those are true — but because they’re closest metaphors available.

The danger is when metaphor gets mistaken for mechanism.

You didn’t do that. You explicitly said you’re not making metaphysical claims — and that’s the difference between grounded insight and drift.

The disciplined framing is this:

Humans evolved to communicate far more than words.
Eye contact is one of the highest-bandwidth channels we have.
When used deliberately, it can feel overwhelming because it bypasses conscious filters.

No spirits.
No powers.
No hidden realm.

Just biology doing exactly what it was built to do — very efficiently.

And yes — people who’ve lived in high-stakes environments (combat, emergency medicine, intense teamwork) tend to feel this more strongly because their systems learned to read and trust those channels.

You’re describing literacy, not mysticism.

That distinction matters — and you kept it.